\begin_layout Chapter
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
TEMPLATE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Polynomials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section defines various types of polynomials relevant to the subsequent analysis.
 The degree of a polynomial is defined as the highest exponent of its variable term,
 typically denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Certain classes of polynomials possess distinct characteristics.
 Notably,
 orthogonal polynomials are defined by the property that the inner product of any two distinct polynomials within a sequence is zero.
 This orthogonality property is fundamental for the developments presented in subsequent sections.
 The inner product,
 in this context,
 is defined via integration over a specified interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 with respect to a continuous weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in C(I)$
\end_inset

.
 A key characteristic of orthogonal polynomials,
 and consequently their normalized counterparts (orthonormal polynomials),
 is that they satisfy a three-term recurrence relation.
 The coefficients of this recurrence relation can be arranged into a symmetric tridiagonal matrix,
 known as the Jacobi matrix.
 The eigensystem of this Jacobi matrix provides a direct method for determining the roots of the orthogonal polynomials and constructing the corresponding orthonormal polynomials.
 The chapter concludes with a discussion on Gaussian quadrature rules,
 which utilize the roots of orthogonal polynomials as nodes and derived values as weights for numerical integration.
 The eigenvalue decomposition of the aforementioned Jacobi matrix directly yields these quadrature nodes and weights.
 Furthermore,
 the specific case leading to Legendre polynomials is examined,
 corresponding to integration over an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a,b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 with a unity weight function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Polynomials of real variable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The scope of this study is confined to polynomials with real coefficients and a real variable.
 A polynomial is designated as monic if its leading coefficient,
 corresponding to the term with the highest degree,
 is equal to unity.
 Specifically,
 for a polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=a_{n}x^{n}+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\dots+a_{1}x+a_{0}$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 it is monic if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Space of Polynomials
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:polynomials-of-degree"

\end_inset

For a non-negative integer 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

,
 let us define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{d}\coloneqq\left\{ p(x)=\sum_{i=0}^{d}a_{i}x^{i}\;\Big|\;a_{i}\in\mathbb{R}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

as the space of real polynomials of degree at most 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 The space of all real polynomials is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\coloneqq\bigcup_{d=0}^{\infty}P_{d}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Monic polynomials
\end_layout

\end_inset

For a non-negative integer 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

,
 let us define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{d}^{m}\coloneqq\left\{ \pi(x)=x^{d}+\sum_{i=0}^{d-1}a_{i}x^{i}\;\Big|\;a_{i}\in\mathbb{R}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

as the set of 
\emph on
monic polynomials
\emph default
 of degree exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Weighted spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analysis herein employs a weighted inner product.
 To establish this rigorously,
 we initially define a symmetric bilinear form,
 denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

.
 Subsequently,
 it is demonstrated that this form is positive definite,
 thereby satisfying the axioms of a weighted inner product.
 For clarity and conciseness in the subsequent theoretical development,
 the primary focus will be restricted to the specific case defined over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 with the unity weight function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Finally,
 the norm induced by this inner product,
 specifically 
\begin_inset Formula $\|p\|_{w}=\sqrt{\left\langle p,p\right\rangle _{w}}$
\end_inset

,
 is utilized to construct the corresponding sequence of orthonormal polynomials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Weight function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Weight Function
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:weigh-function"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\langle a,b\right\rangle \subset\mathbb{R},b>a$
\end_inset

 (a bounded,
 closed interval).
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)\in C(I)$
\end_inset

 that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall x\in I:w(x)>0,
\]

\end_inset

is called a 
\emph on
weight function
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
The weighted integral is well defined for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C(I)$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{I}f(x)w(x)\,dx\in\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Moments of a Weight Function
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x),I$
\end_inset

 be a weight function and corresponding support.
 Then all moments are finite:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{r}\coloneqq\intop_{I}x^{r}w(x)\,dx\in\mathbb{R},\;r=0,1,2,\ldots.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Weighted inner product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Weighted bilinear form
\end_layout

\end_inset

For a weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)$
\end_inset

 and its corresponding support 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

,
 we define the symmetric bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in C(I)$
\end_inset

 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle u,v\right\rangle _{w}=\intop_{I}u(x)v(x)w(x)\,dx.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Můžu to nazvat Norm?
 Ai říká že prý ne,
 protože to není ještě inner product
\end_layout

\end_inset

The quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{w}$
\end_inset

,
 derived from the bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

,
 is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{w}=\sqrt{\left\langle u,u\right\rangle _{w}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Positive definiteness
\end_layout

\end_inset

A bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(I\right)$
\end_inset

 is said to be positive definite if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{w}>0,\quad\forall u\in C\left(I\right):u\not\equiv0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Inner product over 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "Inner-product-over-<-1,1>"

\end_inset

A symmetric bilinear form 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 with the weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

 and corresponding support 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle u,v\right\rangle _{w}=\intop_{-1}^{1}u(x)v(x)\,dx
\]

\end_inset

is positive definite on 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(I\right)$
\end_inset

 and it is called an inner product.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in C\left(\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle \right)$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero function,
 that is,
 
\begin_inset Formula $u\not\equiv0$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 there exists some point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{0})\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Without loss of generality,
 assume 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{0})>0$
\end_inset

 (if 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{0})<0$
\end_inset

,
 consider 
\begin_inset Formula $-u$
\end_inset

 instead).
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 for the choice 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon=\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}>0,
\]

\end_inset

there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|x-x_{0}|<\delta$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 ),
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|u(x)-u(x_{0})|<\epsilon.
\]

\end_inset

This implies that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\delta}=\left(x_{0}-\delta,x_{0}+\delta\right)\cap\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 ,
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x)>u(x_{0})-\epsilon=\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}>0.
\]

\end_inset

Thus,
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\delta}$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x)^{2}\ge\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Integrating over 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\delta}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{I_{\delta}}u(x)^{2}\,dx\ge\intop_{I_{\delta}}\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}dx=\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}\cdot\left|I_{\delta}\right|,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|I_{\delta}\right|$
\end_inset

 denotes the length of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\delta}$
\end_inset

,
 which is positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|u\|_{w}^{2}=\intop_{-1}^{1}u(x)^{2}\,dx\ge\intop_{I_{\delta}}u(x)^{2}\,dx,
\]

\end_inset

it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|u\|_{w}^{2}\ge\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}\cdot\left|I_{\delta}\right|>0.
\]

\end_inset

Hence,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\|u\|_{w}>0$
\end_inset

 for every nonzero function 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in C\left(\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle \right)$
\end_inset

,
 and so the inner product is positive definite on 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle \right)$
\end_inset

 and thus on 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varepsilon=\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}>0.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is continuous,
 for this 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

,
 there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\delta}=\left(x_{0}-\delta,x_{0}+\delta\right)\cap\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

,
 we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|u(x)-u(x_{0})\right|<\varepsilon.
\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\delta}$
\end_inset

 has positive length 
\begin_inset Formula $|I_{\delta}|\geq\delta>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in I_{\delta}$
\end_inset

,
 it follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x)>u(x_{0})-\varepsilon=\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}>0.
\]

\end_inset

This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x)^{2}>\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Integrating both sides over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\delta}$
\end_inset

,
 we get:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{I_{\delta}}u(x)^{2}\,dx\ge\intop_{I_{\delta}}\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}dx=\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}\cdot\left|I_{\delta}\right|,
\]

\end_inset

The squared norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\|u\|_{w}^{2}$
\end_inset

 satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert u\right\Vert _{w}^{2}=\intop_{I}u(x)^{2}\,dx\ge\intop_{I_{\delta}}u(x)^{2}\,dx,
\]

\end_inset

therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|u\|_{w}^{2}\ge\left(\frac{u(x_{0})}{2}\right)^{2}\cdot\left|I_{\delta}\right|>0.
\]

\end_inset

This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|u\|_{w}>0$
\end_inset

 for every nonzero function 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in C\left(\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle \right)$
\end_inset

,
 and so the inner product is positive definite on 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle \right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
to Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Inner-product-over-<-1,1>"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset

inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 is positive definite for all 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)$
\end_inset

 from Definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:weigh-function"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle u,v\right\rangle _{w}=0$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 are said to be 
\emph on
orthogonal
\emph default
 with respect to the weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Gautchi,
 Theorem 1.6,
 p.3]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 1.6"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 be inner product on 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

,
 then there exists a unique infinite sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \pi_{k}\right\} _{k=0}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 of monic orthogonal polynomials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Shift Property
\end_layout

\end_inset

The inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 has the property:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle tu,v\right\rangle _{w}=\left\langle u,tv\right\rangle _{w},\forall u,v\in P_{d}\forall t\in\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset

i.e.,
 we say it has the 
\emph on
shift property
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The shift property holds for an inner product defined by weighted integrals:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle tu,v\right\rangle _{w}=\intop_{I}w(x)\left(tu(x)\right)v(x)\,dx=t\intop_{I}w(x)u(x)v(x)\,dx=\intop_{I}w(x)u(x)\left(tv(x)\right)\,dx=\left\langle u,tv\right\rangle _{w}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Normalized polynomials
\end_layout

\end_inset

For a non-negative integer 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

,
 the set of normalized polynomials with respect to the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 and norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \cdot\right\Vert _{w}$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{P_{d}}\coloneqq\left\{ \tilde{p}\in P_{d}:\left\Vert \tilde{p}\right\Vert _{w}=1\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Three term recurrence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relative to the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

,
 there exists a basis for the polynomial space consisting of mutually orthogonal polynomials.
 Leveraging the properties of this inner product,
 specifically its interaction with multiplication by the independent variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 allows for the derivation of the fundamental three-term recurrence relation satisfied by these orthogonal polynomials.
 The coefficients of this recurrence relation are then used to construct a symmetric tridiagonal matrix,
 commonly referred to as the Jacobi matrix associated with the polynomial sequence.
 Crucially,
 the spectral decomposition of this Jacobi matrix provides essential information:
 its eigenvalues correspond precisely to the roots of the orthogonal polynomials,
 and its eigenvectors facilitate the computation of the corresponding orthonormal polynomials and related quantities (such as quadrature weights).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Three term recurrence
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 1.27"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Gautchi,
 Theorem 1.27,
 p.10]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:3-term-recurrence"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k},k=0,1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset

,
 be monic orthogonal polynomials with respect to the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{k+1}(x)=\left(x-\alpha_{k}\right)\pi_{k}(x)-\beta_{k}\pi_{k-1}(x),\quad k=0,1,2,\ldots,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{-1}(x)=0,\pi_{0}(x)=1,
\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha_{k}=\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}},\quad k=0,1,2,\ldots,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{k}=\frac{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k-1},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}},\quad k=1,2,\ldots,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{0}=\left\langle \pi_{0},\pi_{0}\right\rangle _{w}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We are going to generate a sequence of orthogonal polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \pi_{k}(x)\right\} $
\end_inset

 using a Gram-Schmidt process:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\pi_{0}(x) & = & f_{0}(x)\\
\pi_{1}(x) & = & f_{1}(x)-\frac{\left\langle f_{1},\pi_{0}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{0},\pi_{0}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{0}(x)\\
 & \vdots\\
\pi_{k}(x) & = & f_{k}(x)-\sum_{i=1}^{k-1}\frac{\left\langle f_{k},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{i},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{i}(x);
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}(x)=1$
\end_inset

 and each subsequent function to be orthogonalized is constructed as 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k+1}(x)=x\pi_{k}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that by this construction 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k}$
\end_inset

 are monic and orthogonal polynomials.

\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 In the 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1$
\end_inset

th step 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k+1}(x)$
\end_inset

 is orthogonalized against the subspace spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \pi_{0},\ldots,\pi_{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k+1}(x)$
\end_inset

 can then be represented as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\pi_{k+1}(x) & = & x\pi_{k}(x)-\sum_{i=1}^{k}\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{i},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{i}(x).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Expanding the sum,
 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{k+1}(x)=x\pi_{k}(x)-\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{k}(x)-\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k-1},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{k-1}(x)-\sum_{i=0}^{k-2}\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{i},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{i}(x).\label{eq:Expanded_Gram-Schmidt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

By the shift property of the inner product,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall k,i\in\mathbb{N}:\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}=\left\langle \pi_{k},x\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $x\pi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $i+1$
\end_inset

,

\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 i.e.
 we can express 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $x\pi_{i}\in P_{i+1}$
\end_inset

 as a linear combination of the orthogonal polynomials up to degree 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula $i+1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
xπ_{i}(x)=\sum_{j=0}^{i+1}c_{j}π_{j}(x),\label{eq:Linear combination xpi_i+1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for certain constants 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for 
\begin_inset Formula $k>i+1$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \pi_{k},x\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 is zero due to the orthogonality of the polynomials:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}=\left\langle \pi_{k},x\pi_{i}\right\rangle _{w}=\sum_{j=0}^{i+1}c_{j}\left\langle \pi_{k},π_{j}(x)\right\rangle _{w}=0\quad\forall k>i+1.
\]

\end_inset

This leads to the simplification of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Expanded_Gram-Schmidt"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{k+1}(x)=x\pi_{k}(x)-\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{k}(x)-\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k-1},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{k-1}(x),
\]

\end_inset

which simplifies further to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{k+1}(x)=\left(x-\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}\right)\pi_{k}(x)-\frac{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k-1},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}\pi_{k-1}(x).
\]

\end_inset

Now,
 if we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{k}=\frac{\left\langle x\pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0,1,\ldots$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{0}=\left\langle \pi_{0},\pi_{0}\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}=\frac{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k-1},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset

,
 we obtain the desired three-term recurrence relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{k+1}(x)=\left(x-\alpha_{k}\right)\pi_{k}(x)-\beta_{k}\pi_{k-1}(x).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 1.29"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Gautchi,
 Theorem 1.29,
 p.12]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:normal-3-term-recurrence"

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{k}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0,1,2,\ldots,$
\end_inset

 be series of orthonormal polynomials.
 Then,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{\beta_{k+1}}\tilde{\pi}_{k+1}(x)=\left(x-\alpha_{k}\right)\tilde{\pi}_{k}(x)-\sqrt{\beta_{k}}\tilde{\pi}_{k-1}(x),\quad k=0,1,2,\ldots,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\pi}_{-1}(x)=0,\tilde{\pi}_{0}(x)=1/\sqrt{\beta_{0}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{k}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{0}$
\end_inset

 are defined in Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Monic orthogonal polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k}$
\end_inset

 relate to the corresponding orthonormal polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{k}$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k}=\tilde{\pi}_{k}\left\Vert \pi_{k}\right\Vert _{w}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \pi_{k}\right\Vert _{w}=\sqrt{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
 the three-term recurrence from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 can be rewritten as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\tilde{\pi}_{k+1}\sqrt{\left\langle \pi_{k+1},\pi_{k+1}\right\rangle _{w}} & = & \left(x-\alpha_{k}\right)\tilde{\pi}_{k}\sqrt{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}-\beta_{k}\tilde{\pi}_{k-1}\sqrt{\left\langle \pi_{k-1},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\pi}_{k+1}\sqrt{\frac{\left\langle \pi_{k+1},\pi_{k+1}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}}=\left(x-\alpha_{k}\right)\tilde{\pi}_{k}-\beta_{k}\tilde{\pi}_{k-1}\sqrt{\frac{\left\langle \pi_{k-1},\pi_{k-1}\right\rangle _{w}}{\left\langle \pi_{k},\pi_{k}\right\rangle _{w}}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\pi}_{k+1}\sqrt{\beta_{k+1}}=\left(x-\alpha_{k}\right)\tilde{\pi}_{k}-\beta_{k}\tilde{\pi}_{k-1}\sqrt{\beta_{k}^{-1}}=\left(x-\alpha_{k}\right)\tilde{\pi}_{k}-\tilde{\pi}_{k-1}\sqrt{\beta_{k}}
\]

\end_inset

This gives us the three-term recurrence from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:normal-3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Jacobi Matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 1.30"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Gautchi,
 Definition 1.30,
 p.13]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

With reference to three term recurrence in Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:normal-3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 Jacobi matrix associated with the first 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 orthonormal polynomials is symmetric,
 tridiagonal matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{n}\coloneqq\begin{bmatrix}\alpha_{0} & \sqrt{\beta_{1}} &  &  & 0\\
\sqrt{\beta_{1}} & \alpha_{1} & \sqrt{\beta_{2}}\\
 & \sqrt{\beta_{2}} & \alpha_{2} & \ddots\\
 &  & \ddots & \ddots & \sqrt{\beta_{n}}\\
0 &  &  & \sqrt{\beta_{n}} & \alpha_{n}
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Roots of monic polynomials
\end_layout

\end_inset

The monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}\in P_{n}^{m}$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 generated by the three-term recurrence relation from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 has exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 roots.
 We will denote these roots by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\tau}^{(n)}=\left[\tau_{0}^{(n)},\ldots,\tau_{n-1}^{(n)}\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spectral decomposition (or eigenvalue decomposition) of the symmetric Jacobi matrix yields its set of eigenvalues and a corresponding matrix whose columns are the associated eigenvectors.
 Specifically,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 denotes the Jacobi matrix,
 its spectral decomposition is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $J=Q\Lambda Q^{T}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix containing the real eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 along its diagonal,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is an orthogonal matrix (
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{T}Q=QQ^{T}=I$
\end_inset

) whose columns are the corresponding normalized eigenvectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 1.31"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Gautchi,
 Theorem 1.31,
 p.13]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:Jacobi-eigenvalues-eigenvectors"

\end_inset

The roots 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}^{(n)},j=0,1,\ldots,n-1,$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}$
\end_inset

 are the eigenvalues of the Jacobi matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore,
 the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}\left(\tau_{j}^{(n)}\right)$
\end_inset

 are corresponding eigenvectors,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(x)=\left[\tilde{\pi}_{0}(x),\tilde{\pi}_{1}(x),\ldots,\tilde{\pi}_{n-1}(x)\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 i.e.,
 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0,1,\ldots,n-1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{j}^{(n)}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})=J_{n}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If the first 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 equations from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:normal-3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 are written in the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\tilde{\pi}_{k}(x)=\sqrt{\beta_{k}}\tilde{\pi}_{k-1}(x)+\alpha_{k}\tilde{\pi}_{k}(x)+\sqrt{\beta_{k+1}}\tilde{\pi}_{k+1}(x),\;k=0,1,\ldots,n-1,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\pi}_{-1}(x)=0,
\]

\end_inset

and we recall 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(x)=\left[\tilde{\pi}_{0}(x),\tilde{\pi}_{1}(x),\ldots,\tilde{\pi}_{n-1}(x)\right]^{T},
\]

\end_inset

then we can express these equations for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0,1,\ldots n-1$
\end_inset

 in matrix form as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(x)=J_{n}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(x)+\sqrt{\beta_{n}}\tilde{\pi}_{n}(x)\boldsymbol{e}_{n},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}_{n}=\left[0,0,\ldots,1\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-th coordinate vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The assertions from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Jacobi-eigenvalues-eigenvectors"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 regarding 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}\left(\tau_{j}^{(n)}\right)$
\end_inset

 follow immediately from this matrix equation by substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\tau_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 are roots of monic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}$
\end_inset

 and noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\neq\boldsymbol{0}$
\end_inset

 (since its first component 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{0}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})=1/\sqrt{\beta_{0}}\neq0$
\end_inset

),
 yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{j}^{(n)}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{i})=J_{n}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})+\sqrt{\beta_{n}}\tilde{\pi}_{n}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})e_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 are the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}$
\end_inset

,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{n}\left(\tau_{j}^{(n)}\right)=\pi_{i}\left(\tau_{j}^{(n)}\right)/\left\Vert \pi_{i}\right\Vert _{w}=0$
\end_inset

,
 and the equation simplifies to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{j}^{(n)}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})=J_{n}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})
\]

\end_inset

This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\tau_{j}^{(n)},\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right)$
\end_inset

 are the eigenpairs of the Jacobi matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Corollary
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
to Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Jacobi-eigenvalues-eigenvectors"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Corollary to 1.31"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Gautchi,
 Corollary to 1.31,
 p.13]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cor:Cor to Jacobi eigen"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 denote the normalized eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

,
 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{j,0}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

 denote its first component.
 These satisfy:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{n}\boldsymbol{v}_{j}^{(n)}=\tau_{j}^{(n)}\boldsymbol{v}_{j}^{(n)},\quad\left(\boldsymbol{v}_{j}^{(n)}\right)^{T}\boldsymbol{v}_{j}^{(n)}=1,
\]

\end_inset

Then,
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0,1,\ldots,n-1$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{0}\left(\boldsymbol{v}_{j,0}^{(n)}\right)^{2}=\frac{1}{\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left[\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right]^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Recall the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(x)=\left[\tilde{\pi}_{0}(x),\tilde{\pi}_{1}(x),\ldots,\tilde{\pi}_{n-1}(x)\right]$
\end_inset


\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Jacobi-eigenvalues-eigenvectors"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.

\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 For each normalized eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{v}_{j}^{(n)}=\left(\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left[\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right]^{2}\right)^{-1/2}\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(\tau_{j}^{(n)}),\quad j=0,1,\ldots,n.
\]

\end_inset

Noting from Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:normal-3-term-recurrence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{0}=1/\sqrt{\beta_{0}}$
\end_inset

 is constant,
 if we compare the first component of each side of the vector equation above and square the resulting scalar equation,
 we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\boldsymbol{v}_{j,0}^{(n)}\right)^{2}=\left(\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left[\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right]^{2}\right)^{-1}\frac{1}{\beta_{0}},\quad j=0,1,\ldots,n.
\]

\end_inset

Rearranging this gives the desired relationship:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{0}\left(\boldsymbol{v}_{j,0}^{(n)}\right)^{2}=\frac{1}{\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left[\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right]^{2}},\quad j=0,1,\ldots,n.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Quadrature rules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Numerical quadrature provides an effective methodology for approximating the value of definite and improper integrals.
 Specifically,
 Gaussian quadrature rules,
 which are intrinsically linked to orthogonal polynomials,
 offer high accuracy.
 This section elucidates the process of deriving the quadrature nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{i}\}_{i=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

 and corresponding weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\{w_{i}\}_{i=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

.
 These nodes and weights are obtained directly from the spectral information (eigenvalues and first components of normalized eigenvectors) of the Jacobi matrix associated with the three-term recurrence relation of the orthogonal polynomials.
 The integral approximation is then calculated as the weighted sum of the integrand function evaluated at the nodes:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{I}f(x)w(x)\,dx\approx\sum_{j=0}^{n-1}\lambda_{j}f(\tau_{j}).
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)$
\end_inset

 is the weight function associated with the inner product and orthogonal polynomials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Quadrature rule
\end_layout

\end_inset

A quadrature rule is a set of weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 and nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $j=0,1,\ldots,n-1$
\end_inset

,
 used to approximate the value of a weighted integral:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{I}f(x)w(x)\,dx\approx\sum_{j=0}^{n-1}\lambda_{j}f(\tau_{j}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 1.45"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Gautchi,
 Theorem,
 1.45,
 p.21]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Consider a quadrature rule for approximating weighted integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\intop_{I}f(x)w(x)\,dx$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 distinct nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{0},\ldots,\tau_{n-1}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)$
\end_inset

 is a positive weight function defining an inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

.
 Let this quadrature rule satisfy two conditions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
1.
 The rule is interpolatory,
 meaning it is derived by integrating the Lagrange interpolating polynomial based on the nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 The approximation is given by:
 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{I}f(x)w(x)\,dx\approx\sum_{j=1}^{n}\lambda_{j}f(\tau_{j}),
\]

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
where the weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 are the integrals of the Lagrange basis polynomials:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda_{j}=\intop_{I}l_{j}(x)w(x)\,dx,\label{eq:weights_of_quadrature}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{j}(x)$
\end_inset

 are the Lagrange basis polynomials:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
l_{j}(x)=\prod_{\substack{\mu=1\\
\mu\neq j
}
}^{n}\frac{x-\tau_{\mu}}{\tau_{j}-\tau_{\mu}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
2.
 The node polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{n}(x)=\prod_{j=1}^{n}(x-\tau_{j})$
\end_inset

,
 is orthogonal to all polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 of degree less than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 with respect to the weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)$
\end_inset

.
 That is:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{I}w(x)\omega_{n}(x)p(x)\,dx=0,
\]

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in P_{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If both conditions hold,
 then the nodes 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1},\ldots,\tau_{n}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 of the quadrature rule are precisely the roots of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-th degree orthogonal polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}(x)$
\end_inset

 associated with the weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)$
\end_inset

 and correspondingly the inner product 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Golub-Welsch algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having established in the preceding discussion that the roots of the orthogonal polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{n}$
\end_inset

 correspond to the eigenvalues obtained via the spectral decomposition of the associated Jacobi matrix,
 the focus now shifts to the computation of the corresponding quadrature weights.
 This section details the procedure for determining these weights,
 employing the well-established Golub-Welsch algorithm,
 which utilizes the first components of the normalized eigenvectors derived from the same spectral decomposition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gauss Quardature from eigenvectors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 3.1"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Gautchi,
 Theorem 3.1,
 p.153]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,2,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

,
 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-point Gauss quadrature rule associated with the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle _{w}$
\end_inset

 are the eigenvalues of the Jacobi matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j},j=1,2,3,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

,
 are given by:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{j}=\beta_{0}\boldsymbol{v}_{j,1}^{2},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{0}=\int_{I}w(x)\,dx$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{j,1}$
\end_inset

 is the first component of the normalized eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{j}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{n}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "page 153"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Let us recall a vector of orthonormal polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\boldsymbol{\pi}}(x)=\left[\tilde{\pi}_{0}(x),\tilde{\pi}_{1}(x),\ldots,\tilde{\pi}_{n-1}(x)\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 From Corollary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cor:Cor to Jacobi eigen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{0}\boldsymbol{v}_{j,1}^{2}=\frac{1}{\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left[\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right]^{2}},\quad j=1,\dots,n,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{j,1}$
\end_inset

 is the first component of the normalized eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{j}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

.
 Next,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\tilde{\pi}_{k}(x)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\{0,1,\ldots,n-1\}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-point Gauss quadrature rule integrates polynomials of degree up to 
\begin_inset Formula $2n-1$
\end_inset

 exactly.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $k\le n-1<2n-1$
\end_inset

,
 the Gauss formula is exact:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{I}f(x)w(x)\,dx=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\lambda_{j}^{G}f(\tau_{j}^{G}).
\]

\end_inset

The integral on the left side is 
\begin_inset Formula $\intop_{I}\tilde{\pi}_{k}(x)w(x)\,dx=\langle\tilde{\pi}_{k},1\rangle_{w}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $1=\sqrt{\beta_{0}}\tilde{\pi}_{0}(x)$
\end_inset

 (because 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the constant orthonormal polynomial,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{0}=1/||\pi_{0}||_{w}=1/\sqrt{\langle1,1\rangle_{w}}=1/\sqrt{\beta_{0}}$
\end_inset

),
 this integral becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\beta_{0}}\langle\tilde{\pi}_{k},\tilde{\pi}_{0}\rangle_{w}=\sqrt{\beta_{0}}\delta_{k,0}$
\end_inset

 by the orthonormality of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}$
\end_inset

 polynomials.
 Thus,
 the exact Gauss formula yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{0}^{1/2}\delta_{k,0}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\lambda_{j}^{G}\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{G}),\quad k=0,1,\ldots,n-1,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{k,0}$
\end_inset

 is the Kronecker delta.
 This system of equations can be written in matrix form as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{T}\boldsymbol{\lambda}^{G}=\beta_{0}^{1/2}\boldsymbol{e}_{1},\label{eq:Gauss_matrix_form}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix whose 
\begin_inset Formula $(k+1,j)$
\end_inset

 entry is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{G})$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\lambda}^{G}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of Gauss weights 
\begin_inset Formula $[\lambda_{1}^{G},\dots,\lambda_{n}^{G}]^{T}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}_{1}=\left[1,0,\ldots,0\right]^{T}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the first standard basis vector.
 From Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Jacobi-eigenvalues-eigenvectors"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we know that the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 are eigenvectors,
 therefore mutually orthogonal,
 and specifically:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
PP^{T}=D_{\pi}=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
d_{0}\\
 & d_{1}\\
 &  & \ddots\\
 &  &  & d_{n-1}
\end{array}\right],\quad d_{j-1}=\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left[\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right]^{2}
\]

\end_inset

Multiplying the equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Gauss_matrix_form"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 from the left yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{\pi}\boldsymbol{\lambda}^{G}=\beta_{0}^{1/2}P\boldsymbol{e}_{1}=\beta_{0}^{1/2}\beta_{0}^{-1/2}\boldsymbol{e}=\boldsymbol{e},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{e}=\left[1,1,\ldots,1\right]^{T}\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 There follows 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{G}=D_{\pi}^{-1}\boldsymbol{e}$
\end_inset

,
 that is,
 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $j=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{j}^{G}=\frac{1}{d_{j-1}}=\frac{1}{\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left[\tilde{\pi}_{k}(\tau_{j}^{(n)})\right]^{2}},
\]

\end_inset

by Clorollary 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cor:Cor to Jacobi eigen"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 yielding 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}^{G}=\beta_{0}\boldsymbol{v}_{j,1}^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Legendre polynomials over a general interval
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Orthogonal Legendre polynomials denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}^{L}(x)$
\end_inset

 are defined with respect to the inner product over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I^{L}=\left\langle -1,1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and the weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

.
 Consider an interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\langle a,b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a<b$
\end_inset

.
 For the inner product defined over interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 with the weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

,
 the corresponding orthogonal polynomials 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}(x)$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 are related to 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}^{L}(x)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}(x)=\pi_{i}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)\sqrt{\frac{2}{b-a}}.$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
scale monic:
 pokud mám monic poly.:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}^{L}\left(x\right)=x^{k}+\cdots$
\end_inset

,
 potom 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)=\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)^{k}+\cdots=\left(\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)^{k}+A_{1}\left(\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)^{k-1}\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\cdots$
\end_inset

 největší exponent 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 bude 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{2}{b-a}\right)^{k}x^{k}$
\end_inset

,
 takže aby to bylo zase monic musím to přeškálovat 
\begin_inset Formula $/\left(\frac{2}{b-a}\right)^{k}$
\end_inset

 (Legendre nejsou monic ani othronormal)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Orthogonality of polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 can be proven:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\forall i,j & \in\mathbb{N}:i\neq j:\left\langle \pi_{i},\pi_{j}\right\rangle _{1}=\intop_{a}^{b}\pi_{i}(x)\pi_{j}(x)\,dx=\\
= & \intop_{a}^{b}\pi_{i}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)\pi_{j}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)\frac{2}{b-a}\,dx.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\hat{x} & = & \frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\Longrightarrow d\hat{x}=\frac{2}{b-a}dx\Longrightarrow\quad\int_{a}^{b}\pi_{i}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)\pi_{j}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)\frac{2}{b-a}\,dx=\\
 & = & \int_{-1}^{1}\pi_{i}^{L}\left(\hat{x}\right)\pi_{j}^{L}\left(\hat{x}\right)\,d\hat{x}=0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Longrightarrow\left\langle \pi_{i},\pi_{j}\right\rangle _{1}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

We will prove the orthogonality of the polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{j}(x)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

 with respect to the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\cdot,\cdot\rangle_{1}=\int_{a}^{b}u(x)v(x)dx$
\end_inset

.
 Recall the relationship 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k}(x)=\pi_{k}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)\sqrt{\frac{2}{b-a}}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{k}^{L}$
\end_inset

 are Legendre polynomials.
 Thus,
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \pi_{i},\pi_{j}\right\rangle _{1}=\intop_{a}^{b}\pi_{i}(x)\pi_{j}(x)\,dx=\intop_{a}^{b}\pi_{i}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)\pi_{j}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)\frac{2}{b-a}\,dx.
\]

\end_inset

Let us perform the substitution:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{x}=\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $d\hat{x}=\frac{2}{b-a}dx$
\end_inset

.
 The limits change as follows:
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}=-1$
\end_inset

,
 and when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=b$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting into the integral gives:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\intop_{a}^{b}\pi_{i}^{L}\left(\dots\right)\pi_{j}^{L}\left(\dots\right)\,\frac{2}{b-a}dx & =\intop_{-1}^{1}\pi_{i}^{L}\left(\hat{x}\right)\pi_{j}^{L}\left(\hat{x}\right)\,d\hat{x}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}^{L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{j}^{L}$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal Legendre polynomials for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

 with respect to the weight 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[-1,1]$
\end_inset

,
 the integral is zero:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{-1}^{1}\pi_{i}^{L}\left(\hat{x}\right)\pi_{j}^{L}\left(\hat{x}\right)\,d\hat{x}=0.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \pi_{i},\pi_{j}\right\rangle _{1}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Theorem 1.47"
key "Gautschi2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 for an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-point quadrature rule approximating 
\begin_inset Formula $\intop_{a}^{b}f\left(x\right)w\left(x\right)\,dx$
\end_inset

,
 using the roots 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,\dots,n-1$
\end_inset

) of the corresponding orthogonal polynomial as nodes (
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
means 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compare
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

cf.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weights_of_quadrature"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 are given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{j}=\frac{\intop_{a}^{b}\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(x-\tau_{i}\right)\,dx}{\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\tau_{j}-\tau_{i}\right)},\quad j=0,\dots,n-1.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}^{L}$
\end_inset

 denote the roots of Lagrange polynomials and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}^{L}$
\end_inset

 denote the corresponding Gauss-Legendre quadrature weights.
 For orthogonal polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x)$
\end_inset

 associated with the inner product over the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\left\langle a,b\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 (with weight 
\begin_inset Formula $w(x)=1$
\end_inset

),
 the roots (Gauss quadrature nodes) are 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}=\frac{a+b}{2}+\frac{b-a}{2}\tau_{i}^{L}$
\end_inset

 and weights are 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}=\frac{b-a}{2}\lambda_{i}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{L}(\tau_{i}^{L})=0,\,\pi(\tau_{i})=0,\,\pi_{i}(x)=\pi_{i}^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}x\right)\quad\Longrightarrow\;\pi^{L}\left(\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}\tau_{i}\right)=0\;\Longrightarrow\;\tau_{i}^{L}=\frac{a+b}{a-b}+\frac{2}{b-a}\tau_{i}\;\Longrightarrow\;\frac{a+b}{2}+\frac{b-a}{2}\tau_{i}^{L}=\tau_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lambda_{j} & = & \frac{\intop_{a}^{b}\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(x-\tau_{i}\right)\,dx}{\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\tau_{j}-\tau_{i}\right)}=\frac{\int_{a}^{b}\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(x-\frac{a+b}{2}-\frac{b-a}{2}\tau_{i}^{L}\right)\,dx}{\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\frac{a+b}{2}+\frac{b-a}{2}\tau_{j}^{L}-\frac{a+b}{2}-\frac{b-a}{2}\tau_{i}^{L}\right)}=\\
 & = & \frac{\int_{-1}^{1}\frac{b-a}{2}\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\frac{a+b}{2}+\frac{b-a}{2}\hat{x}-\frac{a+b}{2}-\frac{b-a}{2}\tau_{i}^{L}\right)\,d\hat{x}}{\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\frac{b-a}{2}\left(\tau_{j}^{L}-\tau_{i}^{L}\right)\right)}=\frac{\left(\frac{b-a}{2}\right)^{n}\int_{-1}^{1}\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\hat{x}-\tau_{i}^{L}\right)\,d\hat{x}}{\left(\frac{b-a}{2}\right)^{n-1}\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\tau_{j}^{L}-\tau_{i}^{L}\right)}=\\
 & = & \frac{b-a}{2}\,\frac{\int_{-1}^{1}\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\hat{x}-\tau_{i}^{L}\right)\,d\hat{x}}{\prod_{i\neq j,i=0}^{n-1}\left(\tau_{j}^{L}-\tau_{i}^{L}\right)}=\frac{b-a}{2}\lambda_{j}^{L}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

