\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Equivalence class
\end_layout

\end_inset

We call two Cauchy sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ f_{i}\right\} ,\left\{ g_{i}\right\} \in\mathcal{L}^{2}(I)$
\end_inset

 equivalent if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{i\rightarrow\infty}\left\Vert f_{i}-g_{i}\right\Vert _{L^{2}}=0.
\]

\end_inset

The set of all sequences equivalent to a given sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 is called an equivalence class and is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\left\{ f_{i}\right\} \right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
L2 Space
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\left\{ f_{i}\right\} _{i=0}^{\infty}\in\mathcal{L}^{2}(I)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\left\{ g_{i}\right\} _{i=0}^{\infty}\in\mathcal{L}^{2}(I)$
\end_inset

.
 Let us define the space 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}(I)$
\end_inset

 as an equivalence class space on 
