\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Probability space
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Each thing should probably have its own definition
\end_layout

\end_inset

Probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega,\mathcal{F},\mathbb{P}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a space.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is the all possible elementary outcomes of the random experiment,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}$
\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 is a function that assigns a probability (a real number) to each event 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in the event space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Each subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is called an event.
 An event represents a specific outcome or a set of outcomes we might be interested in.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Stochastic processes and random fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Random variables,
 Realisation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 4.3"
key "LordPowellShardlow2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Lord,
 Definition 4.3,
 p.138]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega,\mathcal{F},\mathbb{P}\right)$
\end_inset

 be a probability space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a measurable space.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a real-valued random variable if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a measurable function from 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega,\mathcal{F}\right)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 To emphasize the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

,
 we may say that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

-measurable random variable.
 The value 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\omega)$
\end_inset

 for a given outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and is called a 
\emph on
realization
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Random vector
\end_layout

\end_inset

A random vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{X}\coloneqq\left(X_{1},X_{2},\ldots,X_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a vector whose elements 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i},i=1,2,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

,
 are random variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Stochastic Process 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 5.2"
key "LordPowellShardlow2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Lord,
 Definition 5.2,
 p.182]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Given a set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}\subset\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and a probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Omega,\mathcal{F},\mathbb{P})$
\end_inset

,
 a real-valued 
\emph on
stochastic process
\emph default
 (also known as a random process) is a collection of real-valued random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X(t):t\in\mathcal{T}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\rightarrow L^{2}\left(\mathcal{T}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Random Field 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 7.1"
key "LordPowellShardlow2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Lord,
 Definition 7.2,
 p.258]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

A 
\emph on
random field
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ u(\boldsymbol{x}):\boldsymbol{x}\in D\right\} $
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $D\subset\mathbb{R}^{d}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of real-valued random variables defined on a probability space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega,\mathcal{F},\mathbb{P}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Expected Value
\end_layout

\end_inset

For a continuous random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with probability density function (PDF) 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

,
 the expected value is defined as:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}\left[X\right]\coloneqq\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}xf\left(x\right)dx.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Covariance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 4.14"
key "LordPowellShardlow2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Lord,
 Definition 4.14,
 p.142]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The covariance of two real-valued random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Cov\left(X,Y\right)\coloneqq\mathbb{E}\left[\left(X-\mu_{X}\right)\left(Y-\mu_{Y}\right)\right]=\mathbb{E}\left[XY\right]-\mu_{X}\mu_{Y},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X}=\mathbb{E}\left[X\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{Y}=\mathbb{E}\left[Y\right]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Autocovariance function
\end_layout

\end_inset

The autocovariance function 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(s,t\right)$
\end_inset

 of a stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X\left(t\right):t\in\mathcal{T}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C\left(s,t\right)\coloneqq\Cov\left(X\left(s\right),X\left(t\right)\right),
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s,t\in\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will assume that the expected value will be equal to 0,
 i.e.,
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[X\right]=0$
\end_inset

.
 If this is not the case,
 instead consider stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ Y\left(t\right):t\in\mathcal{T}\right\} $
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=X-\mathbb{E}\left[X\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Then the expected value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 will be 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Stationary process 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 6.1"
key "LordPowellShardlow2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Lord,
 Definition 6.1,
 p.217]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

A stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X\left(t\right):t\in\mathcal{T}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is called stationary if its covariance function 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(s,t\right)$
\end_inset

 depends only on the difference 
\begin_inset Formula $s-t$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The covariance function of a stationary stochastic process 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X\left(t\right):t\in\mathcal{T}\right\} $
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C\left(s,t\right)=C\left(s-t,0\right)\eqqcolon c\left(s-t\right),
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c\left(\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 is known as the stationary covariance function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Isotropic Random Field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Isotropic Random Field 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 7.14"
key "LordPowellShardlow2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
[Adapted from Lord,
 Definition 7.14,
 p.263]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

A random field 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right):\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is isotropic and stationary if its stationary covariance function 
\begin_inset Formula $c\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)=c^{0}\left(r\right),$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r\coloneqq\left\Vert \boldsymbol{x}\right\Vert _{2}$
\end_inset

,
 for a function 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{0}:\mathbb{R}^{+}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 known as the isotropic covariance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Gaussian Random Field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gaussian distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset

A random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is said to have the Gaussian (or normal) distributionwith mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}>0$
\end_inset

,
 if its probability density function (PDF)
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
to do:
 define earlier
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^{2}}}\exp\left(\frac{-\left(x-\mu\right)^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}}\right),\quad x\in\mathbb{R}.
\]

\end_inset

We denote this by 
\begin_inset Formula $X\sim N\left(\mu,\sigma^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Gaussian Random Field 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Definition 7.5"
key "LordPowellShardlow2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

A Gaussian random field (GRF) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ u\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right):\boldsymbol{x}\in D\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a random field such that for any finite set of points 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}_{1},\ldots,\boldsymbol{x}_{n}\in D$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

),
 the random vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}=\left[u(\boldsymbol{x}_{1}),u(\boldsymbol{x}_{2}),\ldots,u(\boldsymbol{x}_{n})\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

 follows the multivariate Gaussian (or normal) distribution.
 Specifically,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{u}\sim N\left(\boldsymbol{\mu},C\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where the mean vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mu}$
\end_inset

 has components 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}=\mathbb{E}[u(\boldsymbol{x}_{i})]$
\end_inset

 and the covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 has entries 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{ij}=\Cov\left(u(\boldsymbol{x}_{i}),u(\boldsymbol{x}_{j})\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Numerical experiments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Karhunen-Loève expansion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Karhunen-Loève
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X(t)$
\end_inset

 be a Gaussian random field and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(t)=\mathbb{E}[X(t)]=0$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the mean-zero process 
\begin_inset Formula $X(t)-\mu(t)$
\end_inset

.
 We are interested in expressing the sample paths 
\begin_inset Formula $X(t,\omega)-\mu(t)$
\end_inset

 as a series in an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\phi_{j}:j\in\mathbb{N}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{2}(\mathcal{T})$
\end_inset

.
 That is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X(t,\omega)-\mu(t)=\sum_{j=1}^{\infty}\gamma_{j}(\omega)\sqrt{\lambda_{j}}\psi_{j}(t),
\]

\end_inset

where the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{j}$
\end_inset

 are random variables defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{j}(\omega)\coloneqq\langle X(t,\omega)-\mu(t),\phi_{j}(t)\rangle_{L^{2}(\mathcal{T})}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\lambda_{j},\psi_{j}\right)$
\end_inset

 are eigenpairs of the auto covariance operator 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(Cu\right)\left(x\right)\coloneqq\intop_{\mathcal{T}}c\left(x,y\right)u\left(y\right)dy.\label{eq:covariance_operator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Tensor space
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let us have an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional space 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{N}^{x}\coloneqq\spanSed\left\{ \psi_{1},\ldots,\psi_{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and an 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-dimensional space 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{M}^{y}\coloneqq\spanSed\left\{ \phi_{1},\ldots,\phi_{M}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The tensor product space is defined as 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{N}^{x}\otimes V_{M}^{y}:=\spanSed\left\{ \psi_{i}\phi_{j}:i=1,\ldots,N,j=1,\ldots,M\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 and has dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $NM$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
An 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional tensor product space 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{N}^{x}$
\end_inset

 can be formed from 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 one-dimensional spaces 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}^{x_{i}}$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{N}^{x}=V_{1}^{x_{1}}\otimes V_{1}^{x_{2}}\otimes\cdots\otimes V_{1}^{x_{N}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to approximate eigenpairs 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\lambda,u\right)$
\end_inset


\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 of
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(Cu_{i}\right)\left(x\right)\coloneqq\intop_{\mathcal{T}}c\left(x,y\right)u_{i}\left(y\right)dy=\lambda_{i}u_{i}\left(x\right)\quad\forall\boldsymbol{x}\in\mathcal{T}.\label{eq:eigenproblem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let us consider a subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{N}\subset L^{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{T}\right)$
\end_inset

 with a basis 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \psi_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\right\} _{j=0}^{N-1}$
\end_inset

.
 We seek an approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i,N}\in V_{N}$
\end_inset

 to the eigenfunction 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 written as a linear combination of the basis functions:
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{i,N}=\sum_{j=0}^{n-1}\overline{u}_{i,j}\psi_{j}.\label{eq:u_approximation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
Substituting the approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i,N}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:eigenproblem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and applying the Galerkin method,
 meaning
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 we multiply both sides by a base function 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{k}$
\end_inset

 and integrate them over interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

,
 we then obtain a weak formulation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{j=0}^{n-1}\overline{u}_{i,j}\intop_{\mathcal{T}}\intop_{\mathcal{T}}\psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{y}\right)c\left(\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y}\right)\psi_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)d\boldsymbol{x}d\boldsymbol{y}.=\lambda_{i,N}^{n}\sum_{j=0}^{n-1}\overline{u}_{i,j}\intop_{\mathcal{T}}\psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\psi_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)d\boldsymbol{x},\quad\forall k\in\left\{ 0,\ldots,n-1\right\} ,\label{eq:weak_Galerkin}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i,N}$
\end_inset

 is the approximation of the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This can be rewritten in matrix form.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\boldsymbol{u}}_{i}=[\overline{u}_{i,0},\dots,\overline{u}_{i,N-1}]^{T}$
\end_inset

 be the vector representation of the Galerkin approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i,N}$
\end_inset

.
 Define the matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 with entries:
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{k,j}=\intop_{\mathcal{T}}\intop_{\mathcal{T}}\psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{y}\right)c\left(\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y}\right)\psi_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)d\boldsymbol{x}d\boldsymbol{y}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{k,j}=\intop_{\mathcal{T}}\psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\psi_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)d\boldsymbol{x},
\]

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
The weak formulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weak_Galerkin"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 then becomes the generalized eigenvalue problem:
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\nospellcheck off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\overline{\boldsymbol{u}}_{i}=\lambda_{i,N}W\overline{\boldsymbol{u}}_{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\nospellcheck default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
If the kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $c(\boldsymbol{x},\boldsymbol{y})$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and positive semi-definite,
 the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and positive semi-definite.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 (the Gram matrix) is symmetric and positive definite since the basis functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\psi_{j}\}$
\end_inset

 are linearly independent.
 If the basis functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 are orthonormal (i.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{kj}=\delta_{kj}$
\end_inset

),
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is the identity matrix,
 leaving us with the standard eigenvalue problem 
\begin_inset Formula $A\overline{\boldsymbol{u}}_{i}=\lambda_{i,N}\overline{\boldsymbol{u}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset bibtex
LatexCommand bibtex
btprint "btPrintCited"
bibfiles "reference"
options "bibtotoc"
encoding "default"

\end_inset


\end_layout

